@node Duplicate management
@section Duplicate management

@findex anki-editor-extras-duplicates-process
@findex anki-editor-extras-duplicates-cleanup
@findex anki-editor-extras-review-duplicates
@findex anki-editor-extras-suspend-real-duplicates
@findex anki-editor-extras-duplicates-reset
@findex anki-editor-extras-remove-tag
The duplicate management workflow addresses the common problem of accumulating duplicate notes in Anki. After running Anki's built-in ``Find duplicates'' feature (which tags flagged notes with @samp{duplicate}), you can use these commands to process the results from within Emacs.

The command @code{anki-editor-extras-duplicates-process} orchestrates the full workflow in three stages: it first cleans up notes that have already been classified (@ref{Cleanup}), then presents each remaining duplicate for interactive review (@ref{Review}), and finally suspends all confirmed duplicates (@ref{Suspension}).

@menu
* Cleanup::
* Review::
* Suspension::
* Resetting and removing tags::
@end menu

@node Cleanup
@subsection Cleanup

The command @code{anki-editor-extras-duplicates-cleanup} removes the @samp{duplicate} tag from notes that have already been classified. Specifically, it strips @samp{duplicate} from notes tagged both @samp{duplicate} and @samp{real-duplicate}, and from notes tagged both @samp{duplicate} and @samp{no-duplicate}. This ensures that previously reviewed notes do not appear again in the review step.

@node Review
@subsection Review

The command @code{anki-editor-extras-review-duplicates} iterates over all notes still tagged @samp{duplicate} and opens each one in Anki's browser for inspection. For each note, you are prompted with a single-key interface:

@itemize
@item
@samp{r}: tag as @samp{real-duplicate} and remove @samp{duplicate}.
@item
@samp{n}: tag as @samp{no-duplicate} and remove @samp{duplicate}.
@item
@samp{s}: skip this note without changing its tags.
@item
@samp{q}: quit the review loop.
@end itemize

The prompt displays the note ID and how many notes remain, so you can gauge progress.

@node Suspension
@subsection Suspension

The command @code{anki-editor-extras-suspend-real-duplicates} suspends all cards belonging to notes tagged @samp{real-duplicate}. This removes confirmed duplicates from your review queue without deleting them, so they can be unsuspended later if needed.

@node Resetting and removing tags
@subsection Resetting and removing tags

The command @code{anki-editor-extras-duplicates-reset} removes the @samp{duplicate} tag from all notes that have it. This is useful when you want to start the duplicate-detection process from scratch.

The command @code{anki-editor-extras-remove-tag} prompts for a tag name and removes it from every note in your Anki collection that carries it. This is a general-purpose utility not limited to the duplicate workflow.

@node Plot summaries
@section Plot summaries

@findex anki-editor-extras-insert-film-plot-summary
@findex anki-editor-extras-push-plot-summary
The plot summary commands integrate @samp{anki-editor} with @samp{gptel} and @samp{ebib} to generate Anki flashcards for films. The intended workflow is: you visit an Org file whose base name is a Bib@TeX{} key for a film, invoke the command, and it creates a complete Anki note with an AI-generated plot summary.

The command @code{anki-editor-extras-insert-film-plot-summary} uses the current buffer's file name (without extension) as a Bib@TeX{} key. It looks up the film's title, year, and director(s) via @samp{ebib-extras}, then sends a prompt to @samp{gptel} requesting a concise one-paragraph plot summary. The summary is inserted at the end of the buffer under a level-2 heading with all the necessary Anki properties (deck, note type, tags, and front field) pre-filled. After insertion, the command prompts whether to push the note to Anki immediately.

The command @code{anki-editor-extras-push-plot-summary} pushes the Anki note at point and sets its cards' new-card positions starting from a given position. With a prefix argument, you can specify the starting position; otherwise it defaults to 1. This is useful for controlling where the new card appears in your review queue (@ref{Card positioning}).

@node Card positioning
@section Card positioning

@findex anki-editor-extras-set-card-position
@findex anki-editor-extras-set-note-card-positions
Anki assigns each new card a @samp{due} position that determines its order in the new-card queue. The command @code{anki-editor-extras-set-card-position} sets a single card's position via AnkiConnect. Both CARD-ID and POSITION can be integers or numeric strings; POSITION is 1-indexed.

The command @code{anki-editor-extras-set-note-card-positions} operates on all cards belonging to a given note. It retrieves the note's card IDs, sorts them, and assigns consecutive positions starting from START-POSITION (which defaults to 1). For a note with three cards and a start position of 5, the cards receive positions 5, 6, and 7.

